node.text:
One of my patients sent me this video from @jillianmichaels about the new drug semaglutide. She has a gross misunderstanding of obesity and why people fail to lose weight along with how these trials are run.

I forgot to add in a quick segment about the fear of thyroid cancer. It is a very rare type of thyroid cancer that rats are predisposed to. There is no signal that this occurs in humans.

I have many patients on this medicine who finally feel they have a normal appetite. It’s not that they lack willpower, it’s because it’s physiology! Let me know what you think of the video.

node.text: Discussion with @soheefit and @bdccarpenter about obesity and dieting

buttons.text: Visit the COVID-19 Information Center for vaccine resources.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Dr. Spencer Nadolsky on September 12, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Dr. Spencer Nadolsky @DrNadolsky Since shaming those with obesity doesn't help with weight loss. it's possible that shaming those who don't get vaccinated may not help with them getting vaccinated.'.

node.text:
There are individuals who are clearly anti-VAX who will never be convinced with even the best dialogue possible. However there are many people on the fence… and I have even discussed with many of them in my DM‘s. I’ve been very happy to see many who are on the fence get vaccinated after some good discussion and understanding the worry and fears.

Had I called them are idiots for not getting vaccinated it probably wouldn’t have gone the same way. Anyway I bring this up because there are many healthcare professionals who are well-meaning but post in a way that probably isn’t conducive to getting people to change their minds about vaccinations. Many of the same people discuss the futility of shaming those with obesity. There is obviously overlap with this as well. Of course obesity and not getting vaccinated are not the same but there is some overlap. At least enough of some overlap to make this analogy LOL. Anyway, was just thinking about this yesterday❤️

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Dr. Spencer Nadolsky on September 11, 2021. May be a meme of text that says 'When you realize all diets that work for weight loss are through a caloric deficit Plamt-basod @DrNadolsky #Keto Macros'.

node.text: Once you realize it’s all energy balance, you then figure out which foods and dietary patterns help you stay satiated and feel best on your journey. A caloric deficit just means eating fewer calories than you burn. Works even if you have insulin resistance.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Dr. Spencer Nadolsky on September 08, 2021. May be a Twitter screenshot of text that says 'Dr. Spencer Nadolsky @DrNadolsky Eating grass fed beef to get omega 3s is much worse than eating peanut butter to get protein. Stop'.

node.text:
Just a follow up from yesterday. Many folks choose grass fed beef just to get more omega 3s. It’s splitting hairs. You’re much better off looking for omega 3 content from fish which has magnitudes higher levels of omega 3 fatty acids. If you’re going to eat beef, I would go with the one that tastes best to you and not choose based on the small amount of omega 3 content differences. I’m sure my friend @thefarmbabe has much more information on this topic.

You can get omega 3s from non-fish sources as well like walnuts. The issue that some may bring up is that it comes in the form of alpha linolenic acid (ALA) which needs to be converted to EPA/DHA which can be found in fish without needing conversion. Algae supplementation is another option. Whether one actually needs to do this to be healthy I’m not sure. You can also supplement with fish oil, but this has fallen out of favor in recent years. It’s likely best to get better whole food sources.

Anyway, don’t get grass fed beef just for the omega 3 content. It’s silly.

node.text:
I’d say most people have felt guilt from eating something at one point in their life. Some people may even feel it on a daily basis. Remember that it’s all just energy. Some of these foods are more readily overeaten than others and contain fewer nutrients… but you shouldn’t feel guilt from eating them.

Yes, ideally we would eat mostly whole unprocessed nutrient dense foods. But let go of the guilt you get when eating the other foods. In doing so, you’ll be able to focus on improvement. ❤️❤️

Ps I agree with those who have mentioned it’s okay if you’re starving and you have to get what you can to survive ❤️❤️
